  <!-- ============ METHODOLOGY ============ -->
  <section class="container-prose pt-16 pb-10">
    <div class="reveal mb-6">
      <h2 class="section-heading">Methodology — the discipline under the measurements</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="narrative reveal">
      <p>
        The project's metric pipeline is from-scratch (gate IR-2): graded-gain nDCG with <code>gain = 2^rel − 1</code>, discount <code>log2(i+1)</code>, iDCG over full qrels. <code>pytrec_eval</code> runs alongside as a cross-check, not a replacement. |Δ| has been ≤ 2e-3 on every one of the 18 bench cells; Recall@k is bit-exact on 7/9.
      </p>
      <p>
        CUDA timing uses <code>torch.cuda.Event</code>, not <code>time.perf_counter()</code>. FAISS <code>IndexFlatIP</code>, top-k = 100, batch size 128. Seed 1729 everywhere — Ramanujan's taxicab number. Each cell writes a per-query-results block (schema §5.7) so downstream analyses like Phase 6 can join on <code>query_id</code> without re-running the pod.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two disciplines emerged from costly lessons. After the <code>bert-base</code> checkpoint mis-targeting (dot-trained being L2-normalized, −0.08 nDCG): <em>the encoder declares its similarity, the harness reads it.</em> Forgetting to declare fails at class-creation time. After the transformers 5.x silent head-mask drop: <em>one-cell sanity check before any multi-hour sweep, verifying the independent variable actually moves the measurement.</em>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ WHAT REMAINS ============ -->
  <section class="container-prose pb-20">
    <div class="reveal mb-6">
      <h2 class="section-heading">What remains · Phase 9</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="narrative reveal">
      <p>
        Phase 9 — the 100% milestone — is a 5-to-7-page opinionated technical note, arXiv-ready. Not a survey. Not a system paper. A short document that says: <em>here is what we measured, here is what changed our mind, here is what we now believe about alternative encoders for dense retrieval, and here is exactly where we were wrong.</em>
      </p>
      <p>
        The <code>query_level_sensitivity.parquet</code> artifact (22,878 rows across 6 encoders × ~300–650 queries × 3 modes × 3 datasets) sits ready for the cross-phase join: Phase 6's failure taxonomy joined on <code>query_id</code> against Phase 8's per-query shuffle delta. That join runs locally and does not need pod time. It answers questions like: <em>are `LEN-LONG` queries more position-sensitive? are `PARAPHRASE` failures position-insensitive?</em>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal mt-8 pull-quote">
      The transformer is not uniquely the right inductive bias for dense retrieval. But it is not uniquely wrong either. The honest conclusion — measured, not argued — is that for a meaningful slice of real retrieval workloads, a 6.4M-parameter BiLSTM sits on the Pareto frontier next to MiniLM and does so with far less machinery. That is the result Vitruvius exists to produce.
    </div>
  </section>

